The property manager, David Thompson, says it is the ideal territory for them.
Here at Threave, we have a fantastic area for bats," he said.
We have old buildings, many old trees and all the right habitat.
However, there is still much to be learned about bats, and the work we do here and at other properties will help us to understand better what they need to thrive."
He stresses the importance of checking for bats before maintenance work is carried out on the property, as a colony of bats could be destroyed unintentionally and 400 breeding females and young could be killed, which would wipe out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them, as well as to destroy their colonies.
The Scottish-born Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish Wildlife Trust officer, has urged the public to help.
He said: "We still have much to learn about bats and many other species about which we know little about their populations."
