Syria ready to welcome back refugees, says Foreign Minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and is seeking help to rebuild a country devastated by a war that has been going on for more than seven years.
In a speech to the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that conditions in the country were improving.
The situation on the ground is today more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism.
The government is still trying to rehabilitate the areas destroyed by the terrorists in an attempt to restore normality.
All the conditions are in place for the voluntary return of refugees who had to leave their country because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and livelihoods.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the war began in 2011.
There are still six million people in the country who need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem acknowledged that the Syrian regime would welcome help in rebuilding the devastated country.
But he also emphasized that he would not accept conditional aid or aid from countries that had promoted the insurgency.
