Update on the red tide: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The new report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (FFWC) shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular bloom conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The red tide blooms extend approximately 130 miles along the coast from Pinellas County to Lee County.
Irregular parcels can be found as far as 10 miles from the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer than last week.
Red tides have also been detected in the county of Pasco.
During the past week, medium concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County and along its coast, low concentrations along the coast of Hillsborough County, low concentrations along the coast of Manatee County, low concentrations along the coast of Sarasota County and its offshore waters, low concentrations along the coast of Charlotte County, low concentrations along the coast of Lee County and its offshore waters, and low concentrations along the coast of Collier County.
Reports of respiratory irritation continue in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
There have been no reports of respiratory irritation in the northwest of Florida during the past week.
